snippet.textDisplay: This is waaaaaay better than the SNES version. Compared them to see what the fuss was about. The SNES versions treble is barely audible, so all you can hear is the (over-powering) drums and the melody is almost muted. Can see that the quality of the Genesis instruments isn't great, but overall this version, whilst harsher, is certainly more clear and not completely overpowered by drums + bass.

snippet.textDisplay: +Ghreivyn yeah, no.  The Genesis has a distinct metalic sound to it.  It works best in games that take advantage of it.  But every game that came out with the same music on it for SNES and Gen, sounds better on the SNES.  The reverberation on the SNES is due to the way the chip worked. The SNES is a much better piece of hardware, benefiting from coming out later than the GEN.  The SMS is superior on technical level to the NES, but the same doesnt hold true for the next gen.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thunder Force 3 sounded MUCH better than Thunder Spirits. That's probably the best example of where the Genesis/MD excelled. 

Basically, the Mega Drive's modular synthesis was better for electronic, high tempo compositions, and the SNES's sample based music was better for "out the box" "orchestral" sounding music. A better music programmer could generally get more out of the Genesis, but a mid range one could do better with the set samples of the SNES.

snippet.textDisplay: @SyriusBelsferg It wasn't just the Genesis, pretty much 50% of all games on every platform back then never made adequate use of their respective sound hardware. There were plenty of great soundtracks on the Genesis- the Sonic games, Streets of Rage 1 and 2 and all of Treasure and Konami's games are the obvious examples, but then there were the hidden gems like ResQ, Dangerous Seed, Socket, Verytex, Jewel Master, Shura no Mon, ATP Tour Championship Tennis, M.U.S.H.A., The Hybrid Front...
